  "texts": [
    "see Oguri et al. 2014; Foxley-Marrable et al. 2018), which, in short, states that the same lens potential and light distribution can be produced by a low dark matter fraction and many low-mass (and less luminous) stars, or a high dark matter fraction and fewer but brighter stars.",
    "Finally, the masssheet degeneracy (Falco et al. 1985; Gorenstein et al. 1988), i.e.",
    "scaling the lens galaxy mass distribution and adding a constant surface mass density (mass-sheet), leaves observables such as the image positions, shapes, and flux ratios, unchanged but affects the κ, γ.",
    "Although there are ways to mitigate these effects, e.g.",
    "by breaking the mass-sheet degeneracy through modelling of kinematics data (see Shajib et al. 2024) or explicitly modelling substructures (see Vegetti et al. 2024), the complexity of the true lens potential and the corresponding quality of a macromodel will eventually affect microlensing measurements."
  ],
